r}2{\textless}/sup{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}p{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} = 0.395) indicated that D1 inhibition was associated with a significant reduction in PSI levels from TF to TP (p = 0.001, $\eta${\textless}sup{\textgreater}2{\textless}/sup{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}p{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} = 0.731), whereas no significant difference between the tasks was observed for D2 inhibition (p = 0.078, $\eta${\textless}sup{\textgreater}2{\textless}/sup{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}p{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} = 0.305). These results suggest that D1 and D2 inhibitions of the soleus H-reflex are differentially modulated during the performance of plantarflexion FT and PT. The reduced level of ongoing PSI during PT suggests that, in comparison to FT, there is a larger reliance on inputs from muscle spindles primary afferents when the neuromuscular system is required to maintain position-controlled plantarflexion contractions.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
